[[File:Lauren States on Cloud Computing.jpg|thumb|Lauren States being interviewed]] '''Lauren States''' (born 1956) is a former [[Chief technology officer|Chief of Technology]]<ref name=forbes>[https://www.forbes.com/2008/11/06/030.html Forbes interview]</ref> and then Vice President of Strategy and Transformation for [[IBM]]'s Software Group Sales Division.
==Life== States was born in 1956 and she originally intended to be an [[actuary]]. However she learnt to program in [[COBOL]] and discovered a gift for technology.<ref name=forbes/> She has a degree in Economics from the [[Wharton School of the University of Pennsylvania]].<ref name=witi>[http://www.witi.com/center/witimuseum/halloffame/137874/Lauren-States-Advanced-Leadership-Initiative-Fellow-Harvard-University/ Women in Technology International Hall of Fame page]</ref>
She joined IBM as a trainee and worked her way up as an engineer resisting the invitations to become a manager.<ref name=forbes/>
States was inducted into the [[Women in Technology International#WITI Hall of Fame|Women In Technology International Hall of Fame]] in 2014.<ref name=witi/>
