{{Infobox Mobile phone |name = Motorola A910 |image = Motorola A910 opened.jpg |caption = Motorola A910 opened |imagesize = 150px |slogan = |manufacturer = [[Motorola]] |carrier = |available = Q1 2006 |screen = 240 x 320 pixels, TFT with 256k colors |camera = 1.3 [[Megapixels#Megapixel|megapixels]] 1280 x 1024 pixels, with full-screen viewfinder |os = MontaVista [[Linux]] OS (not [[MOTOMAGX]]) |input = Dialpad keyboard |cpu = [[Intel]] [[XScale]] processor |ringtone = |memory = 48MB RAM |memory_card = SD/MMC expandable to 2 GB |storage = |networks = [[GSM]] Tri-band (900/1800/1900) |connectivity = [[GPRS]] Class 10, [[Universal Serial Bus#Mini_and_micro|Enhanced Mini USB]], BCM2045 Bluetooth 2.0 (+[[Bluetooth profile#Advanced Audio Distribution Profile .28A2DP.29|A2DP]]), [[Wi-Fi]] 802.11 b/g |battery = [[Li-ion]] 1000 mAh |size = 93 x 51 x 23 mm, 88 cc |weight = 127 g |music = AMR-NB, AMR-WB, XMF, WMA v9, WAV, AAC, EAAC+, MP3, RealAudio, MP4 |series = }}
The '''Motorola A910''' is a [[Flip (form)|clamshell]] mobile phone from [[Motorola]], which uses MontaVista [[Linux]] as the [[operating system]].
Motorola started selling this phone in the first quarter of the year 2006. Utilizing a balanced Linux-[[Java (software platform)|Java]] operating system and [[Wi-Fi]] connectivity, the Motorola A910 surpasses its predecessors with user-friendly features, everything from text messaging to email management. It is also the only clamshell phone from Motorola with Wi-Fi, as well as the only non-touchscreen Motorola with Wi-Fi in [[Europe]].
== Features == The phone is supplied with a number of applications including a [[Post Office Protocol|POP]] and [[IMAP]] email client, Opera web browser, calendar and a viewer for PDF and Microsoft Office files. Calendar and address book can be synchronized with a [[Microsoft Exchange Server|Microsoft Exchange]] or [[SyncML]] server. The phone has a 1.3 [[megapixel]] camera with Self Portrait Viewfinder External Display and photo lighting, recording still and video images. [[RealPlayer]] is included to play sound audio files and streamed audio and video. The phone has 48 [[megabyte]]s of internal flash memory for storing user data and a slot for a [[microSD]] card, which supports additional 2 GB of storage. Both [[Bluetooth]] and USB are provided for communication with another computer. Character entry is made by the keypad interface.<ref>[http://www.gsmarena.com/motorola_a910-1233.php GSM Arena] Full phone specifications</ref>
==Linux enthusiasts== This phone is popular with Linux enthusiasts. It is able to establish an Ethernet connection between the phone and another computer over [[USB]], [[Bluetooth]] or [[Wi-Fi]]. One can then [[telnet]] to the phone and be presented with a [[Bash (Unix shell)|bash]] prompt. From the prompt one can, for example, mount a NFS drive(s) on the phone. The underlying operating system, Motorola EZX is Linux based, its kernel is open source. With the source code hosted on ''opensource.motorola.com'', it is possible to recompile and replace the kernel for this operating system. However Motorola did not publish a software development kit for native applications. Instead, they are expecting third party programs to be written in [[Java Platform, Micro Edition|Java ME]]. The [[OpenEZX]] website is dedicated to providing free opensource software for this phone and others using the same OS.
